        <Document ID="163">
            <Title>The Weyrlands</Title>
            <Text>The Weyrlands
Westernmost province
Role in Story
Most remote and “other” part of the Saskan Lands. Mountainous, hilly. Where the [wind lords] and [herbalists] have their centers.  The source of both the main rivers. The source of change. The lacunae. The nothing-that-is. The empty set that makes unity always a matter of change and development rather than solidity.

Love. Healing.
Related Characters
Morning Thunder. 

Seasons
In the region around the upper [Barbo], idyllic rolling waters, hillsides full of plants, flowers, herbs. Not eternal spring, but something like that year-round.  
In the region around the upper [Bloo], the highest peaks in the Saskan Lands.  The snowiest region.
Unique Features
The only province that lies in part outside of the more-or-less recognized borders of Saskantinon. Not the only mountainous/hilly regions (see: Eelan, Bordaloon and Salofess), but the most mountainous and remote.
A good number of fairly well-maintained roads/paths run through the region. 
Description
The name “weyr” is borrowed from Anne McCaffrey’s fictional world of Pern. It implies that “dragons” now live or once lived here.  In my world, this serves as an allusion to the long-lost knowledge of / desire for flight. 
The “wind lords” of New Weyr and the region around the town will be a key into this part of the story, but I am still working through how to approach this in a subtle, interesting way. New Weyr is the only town located on a mountain. And like New Harvest, it will be concealing some secrets.  I am thinking caves/underground installations with allusions to both flying animals and flying machines.  
Sights
Main towns are New Weyr and New Harvest.  New Harvest sits above an underground town called Freedom.

Sounds
Many small waterfalls, rapids. Lots of non-sentient wildlife, though birds and flying insects are very rare. Many caves and some cenotes.

Smell


Notes

